{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Deploy an internal low-interaction honeypot/tarpit on the LAN (decoy service(s) that emulate common targets) to attract and engage network scanners, slow their reconnaissance, and capture tooling, timing and behavior for forensic analysis.",
  "comments": "I deployed a LAN honeypot (implemented using the provided squid device type) and connected it to the cisco-switch so it is present on the same segment as the compromised host. This places a decoy service on the LAN to attract/engage scanners and provide telemetry about scanning behavior while the attacker remains active. During implementation I attempted to also link the compromised UbuntuComputer directly to the honeypot but that link attempt failed with a 'No available slots' error on the UbuntuComputer. I did not delete the existing inline Snort link (which is actively protecting and blocking reconnaissance) in order to preserve that protection. As a result the honeypot is reachable on the LAN via the switch and will still collect scanner/traffic hits from other hosts; it will slow reconnaissance effectiveness and provide forensic data without removing or disconnecting the compromised host. Recommended next steps: 1) Collect honeypot logs/traffic to observe scan tooling and timing; 2) Tune IPS/ firewall rules to throttle scan behaviors (rate-limit/connection anomaly) and correlate honeypot alerts with Snort detections; 3) If required, free a port on UbuntuComputer by planned topology change (only if preserving inline Snort protection) to allow additional link topologies.",
  "device_identifier": "honeypot-1",
  "commands": [
    "add_network_device(\"squid\", \"honeypot-1\")",
    "link_network_devices(\"honeypot-1\", \"cisco-switch\")",
    "link_network_devices(\"UbuntuComputer\", \"honeypot-1\")  // Attempted but failed: No available slots on UbuntuComputer"
  ]
}
